Male":"1287–Afdød","1295–Male":"1295–Afdød","1305–1346":"1305–1346","1245–1279":"1245–1279","–Female":"Afdød","1330":"1330","1295":"1295","1305":"1305","1346":"1346","abt 1305":"omkring 1305","1279":"1279","1268":"1268","1245":"1245","1287":"1287","1265":"1265","after 1330":"efter 1330","about 1286":"omkring 1286","about 1264":"omkring 1264","about 1265":"omkring 1265","about 1287":"omkring 1287","about 1295":"omkring 1295","after 1279":"efter 1279","of Denton, Yorkshire,  England":"Denton, Jórvík, England, United Kingdom","of Denton, Yorkshire, England":"Denton, Jórvík, England, United Kingdom","Wolsington, Yorks., England":"Jórvík, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"about 1265–after 1330":"circa 1265–na 1330","1265–1330":"1265–1330","1268–Male":"1268–Overleden","1265–Female":"1265–Overleden","1287–Male":"1287–Overleden","1295–Male":"1295–Overleden","1305–1346":"1305–1346","1245–1279":"1245–1279","–Female":"Overleden","1330":"1330","1295":"1295","1305":"1305","1346":"1346","abt 1305":"circa 1305","1279":"1279","1268":"1268","1245":"1245","1287":"1287","1265":"1265","after 1330":"na 1330","about 1286":"circa 1286","about 1264":"circa 1264","about 1265":"circa 1265","about 1287":"circa 1287","about 1295":"circa 1295","after 1279":"na 1279","of Denton, Yorkshire,  England":"Denton, Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","of Denton, Yorkshire, England":"Denton, Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Wolsington, Yorks., England":"Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1265–after 1330":"about 1265–after 1330","1265–1330":"1265–1330","1268–Male":"1268–Deceased","1265–Female":"1265–Deceased","1287–Male":"1287–Deceased","1295–Male":"1295–Deceased","1305–1346":"1305–1346","1245–1279":"1245–1279","–Female":"Deceased","1330":"1330","1295":"1295","1305":"1305","1346":"1346","abt 1305":"about 1305","1279":"1279","1268":"1268","1245":"1245","1287":"1287","1265":"1265","after 1330":"after 1330","about 1286":"about 1286","about 1264":"about 1264","about 1265":"about 1265","about 1287":"about 1287","about 1295":"about 1295","after 1279":"after 1279","of Denton, Yorkshire,  England":"Denton, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","of Denton, Yorkshire, England":"Denton, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Wolsington, Yorks., England":"Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"le","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Vietnamese Thanh, Hung, Minh, Dung, Tuan, Hai, Hoa, Thuy, Son, Anh, Long, Hoang.  Chinese Hong, Sang, Chi, Dong, Tong, Lai, Hang, Man, Han, Ho, Phoung, Chan.  Korean Tam, Phong, Nam, Thai, Tuong, Chung, Thach, Tinh, Manh, Tham, Uyen, Vang.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 樂, meaning ‘happiness’ in Chinese: from the first element of the personal name Le Fu (樂父), style name of Yan, son of the Duke Dai of Song (ruler of the state of Song, reigned 799–766  BC ). Yan's grandson Le Ju (樂莒) inherited Le (樂) as his surname.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 勒: (i) from the second element of the placename Shu-Le (疏勒), an ancient state (located in present-day Xinjiang Uyghur autonomous region) during the Western Han dynasty (206  BC –25  AD ). (ii) a surname near the Bohai Sea region during the Han dynasty (206  BC –220  AD ). (iii) a surname traced back to the Hun ethnic group in northern China during the Jin dynasty (265–420  AD )."],"variants":[{"name":"Yue","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese: Chi, Feng, Gang, Wei, Chun, Guo, Jin, Kin, Ping, Yan, Yun, Zhang, Chau, Du, Hau, Hung, My, Sau.","Chinese:","Mandarin form of the surname 岳 (or 嶽), meaning ‘high mountain’ in Chinese: traced back to Si Yue (四岳 or 四嶽), said to be the title of an official post in charge of sacrificial rituals on the site of famous mountains during the reign of the legendary Emperor Yao (<i>c.</i> 24th century  BC ) and Emperor Shun (<i>c.</i> 23rd century  BC )."]},{"name":"Lok","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Ping, Tat, Wing, Ying Lin, Chi Ming, Ching Wah, Chun, Chung Man, Han, Kam, Kam Tim, Kin.","Chinese: Cantonese form of the surname 樂, see   Le   1.","Chinese: Cantonese form of the surnames 陸, 鹿, 逯 and 禄, see   Lu   5 and (7-9)."]},{"name":"Li","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Wei, Ming, Li, Jian, Hong, Yan, Ping, Jing, Yong, Ying, Hui, Jin, Min, Chung.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 李, meaning ‘plum’: (i) said to have been adopted in place of the Chinese surname 理 (also pronounced Li; meaning ‘rules’ in Chinese) by Li Zhen (利貞), son of an official called Li Zheng (理徵) in the late Shang dynasty (1600–1046  BC ). It is said that Li Zhen's father incurred the displeasure of King Zhou of Shang (died 1046  BC ) and Li Zhen fled to a wasteland area, where he survived on wild plums. After his return to civilization, he changed his surname to Li (李 ‘plum’), a word with the same pronunciation. The original surname, 理, is said to be from Li Guan (理官), the name of a post of officials in charge of legislation in ancient China. Li Er (李耳), also known as Lao Tzu or Lao Zi, traditionally regarded as the founder of Taoism, is believed to have been a descendant of Li Zhen. (ii) adopted as a surname by the Chi Li (叱李) family from the Xianbei ethnic group during the Northern Wei dynasty (386–534  AD ). (iii) in the early years of the Tang dynasty (618–907  AD ), sixteen high officials with different surnames were granted the surname Li (李), the surname of the royal family of the Tang dynasty, by Emperor Taizong of Tang (died 649  BC ), because of their contributions to the establishment of the Tang regime. (iv) the surname can also be traced back to several minority ethnic groups in ancient China.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 黎, meaning ‘black’ or ‘multitude’ in ancient Chinese: (i) from Li (黎), the name of an ancient state (located in Changzhi in Shanxi province) during the Shang dynasty (1600–1046  BC ), which was annexed in the Western Zhou dynasty (1046–771  BC ) and later granted to Fengshu, also known as Li Hou (黎侯, 'Marquis Li'). (ii) adopted as a surname by the Su Li (素黎) family, members of the Xianbei ethnic group, during the Northern Wei dynasty (386–534  AD )."]}]},{"name":"Vavasour","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English: status name for a feudal tenant ranking immediately below a baron, Old French  <i>vavas(s)our</i>,  <i>vavasseur</i>, Latin  <i>vassus vassorum</i> ‘vassal of vassals’."],"variants":[{"name":"Vavasseur","meanings":["English:  see  Vavasour  ."]},{"name":"Bavister","meanings":["English:   Titford   suggests that this is a late variant of   Vavasour  . It would be a dissimilated form of  <i>Vavister</i> and  <i>Vavester</i>, variants of  <i>Vavasour</i> that are evidenced in Lincs, also in Cambs, whence the name spread into Beds. Compare Willa Vavister, 1579 in   IGI   (Scopwick, Lincs); Thomas Vavister, 1615 in   IGI   (Cranwell, Lincs); Mary Vavester, 1708, Joseph Vavisor, 1738 in   IGI   (New Sleaford, Lincs)."]},{"name":"Vawser","meanings":["English: reduced form of   Vavasour  ."]}]},{"name":"Mauger","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French and Channel Islands (Guernsey and Jersey): from the Old French (Norman) personal name <i>Maug(i)er</i>, <i>Malg(i)er</i>, from ancient Germanic <i>Madalgar(i)</i>, <i>Malger</i>, composed of the elements <i>madal</i> ‘council, meeting’ and <i>gar(i)</i> ‘spear’, or from <i>Amalgar(i)</i>, with the first element <i>amal</i> ‘capable, brave, eager’. Compare   Major  ,   Monger  , and   Munger  .","Probably also an altered form of German   Mager  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Maugeri","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Carmine, Ignazio, Salvatore, Angelo, Camillo, Giuseppe, Orazio, Pietro.","Italian (southern):","variant of <b>Malgeri</b>, from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Madalgari</i> or <i>Amalgari</i> (see   Mauger  )."]},{"name":"Major","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from the personal name <i>Malg(i)er</i>, <i>Maug(i)er</i>, an Old French form of ancient Germanic <i>Madalgar(i)</i> (see   Mauger  ).","Hungarian: from a shortened form of <i>majorosgazda</i> (see   Majoros  ) or a derivative of German   Meyer  .","Polish, Czech, and Slovak: from the military rank <i>major</i> (derived from Latin <i>maior</i> ‘greater’), a word related to English <i>mayor</i> and the German surname   Meyer  ."]},{"name":"Mangieri","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Gaspar, Mario, Angelo, Arsenio, Mafalda, Orazio, Rocco, Silvio.","Italian: variant of <b>Malgeri</b>, from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Madalgari</i> or <i>Amalgari</i> (see   Mauger  )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Sir Mauger le Vavasour was born about 1265, in Denton, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom as the son of Mauger Vavasour and Agnes. He married Alice Revell about 1286, in Denton, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. He died after 1330."},"et":{"about 1265–after 1330":"umbes 1265–pärast 1330","1265–1330":"1265–1330","1268–Male":"1268–Surnud","1265–Female":"1265–Surnud","1287–Male":"1287–Surnud","1295–Male":"1295–Surnud","1305–1346":"1305–1346","1245–1279":"1245–1279","–Female":"Surnud","1330":"1330","1295":"1295","1305":"1305","1346":"1346","abt 1305":"umbes 1305","1279":"1279","1268":"1268","1245":"1245","1287":"1287","1265":"1265","after 1330":"pärast 1330","about 1286":"umbes 1286","about 1264":"umbes 1264","about 1265":"umbes 1265","about 1287":"umbes 1287","about 1295":"umbes 1295","after 1279":"pärast 1279","of Denton, Yorkshire,  England":"Denton, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","of Denton, Yorkshire, England":"Denton, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Wolsington, Yorks., England":"Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":